Calamos reworks leadership structure, expands through acquisition - Naperville Sun





























































Suburbs 
Naperville Sun 
Naperville Sun News 



Calamos reworks leadership structure, expands through acquisition








Daina Saleh / Naperville Sun
John P. Calamos Sr. stands beside newly appointed president Robert Behan, who has been part of Calamos Investments for almost a decade.
John P. Calamos Sr. stands beside newly appointed president Robert Behan, who has been part of Calamos Investments for almost a decade. (Daina Saleh / Naperville Sun)



Robert Behan named Calamos presidentPrivacy Policy





Calamos Investments has a global reach but for the past 10 years it has called Naperville home.And now the investment management firm, founded by Chicago area native John P. Calamos Sr. in 1977, has made major moves regarding its leadership structure and an expansion of offered products.The firm has appointed Robert Behan as president, and it has also recently acquired Phineus Partners LP in San Francisco and opened an office in Miami, Fla.In addition the company also recently appointed four members of its current investment team, John Hillenbrand, David Kails, Nick Niziolek and Eli Pars, as co-chief investment officers,

"During our expansion, these four investment team members emerged as strong leaders and have demonstrated exceptional capabilities as they have taken on more responsibilities," Calamos said. "We want each of the team to be really focused in those particular areas of responsibilities. Again, this is what we've been working for a number of years. We felt very comfortable that we got to this place where we can announce this."In an earlier statement Calamos said the leadership team will give clients "a more focused approach and the staff better bench strength."The move brings investment executives with decades of experience in their respective fields to the table, according to Calamos. The four will lead different types of investment classes — global equities, U.S. growth equities, convertible securities and closed-end funds.Appointing Behan, formerly head of global distribution, as president further shows the firm's evolution and expansion plans both in the country as well as globally, Calamos said.

"In recent years, Bob has taken on significant responsibilities beyond his role as head of global distribution and has been integral to many of our strategic growth initiatives across our organization," Calamos said.Behan, who was part of opening the London office last year and is over-seeing the opening of a Florida office and acquisition deals with hedge fund firm Phineaus LP, adds: "We've worked together for years, and we are in some ways still a family run business.""We actually think it's a little bit of the future of the business to put the decision-making power at a multiple level, which is closer to potentially the process and the people. And we looked at a lot of companies our size and bigger and we determined that we have the right people in the right spots that have really emerged over the years handling additional responsibilities," Behan said in explaining the shift in leadership roles.Both Calamos and Behan say they are excited to announce the upcoming acquisition of Phineus Partners LP, a global long/short hedge fund started by Michael D. Grant in 2002 in California, to further expand the firm's product suite."We are pleased to welcome Michael and his team to Calamos Investments," Calamos says. "As one of the first entrants into the liquid alternative space more than 20 years ago, we continue to expand our presence in the space. Michael's strategy will be a welcome addition to our lineup."Identifying strategies and staying on top of the global current is what Calamos Investment is all about, Behan says, adding that John Calamos just gave an interview on his market outlook on CNBC this past August. "John has been watching and anticipating the market for 40 plus years, and especially when things get a little crazy, advisers are always looking to John to see what he's thinking on this," Behan emphasizes.Calamos is happy to share his thoughts: "We are still positive on growth, although it's slow growth. We don't think we are in a recession. We are in a slow growth area and at this part of the investment cycle we will continue to see more volatility. From an investor point of view what I've learned over the years is you should not get whip sawed out of the market. I do think we have to think globally, we are in a global economy. And we look at that very carefully."Calamos Investment, which employs about 350 mostly local residents in its headquarters, built up the Calamos Campus, including Hotel Arista, on the northeast corner of Interstate 88 and Route 59 in 2005, has both feet firmly planted in Naperville. Calamos said he is actually looking into expanding the campus to both sides of Route 59.."John Calamos takes the role as a corporate citizen in the Naperville community very seriously, having a presence in the Naperville Area Chamber of Commerce and Choose DuPage, and a number of community organizations, and we do extensible charity giving in the area," adds Jennifer McGuffin, VP and director of corporate communications.An apprentice program and an internship program have both grown in reputation attracting talent from near and far."It has gotten highly competitive," Behan says. Calamos added that it's exciting to see so much talent available.Daina Saleh is a freelance reporter for the Naperville Sun.

Copyright
            © 2017, Naperville Sun
 John P. Calamos Sr. Naperville















